      "<li><strong>Marriage Story</strong> â€“ Interesting to see two sides of a conflict.  Itâ€™s sad but thereâ€™s humor in the movie and itâ€™s well acted</li><li><strong>The Editor</strong> â€“ I started off not super impressed, but as the movie went on and I started to get the references and the humor, I started to really appreciate it</li><li><strong>A Dark Song</strong> â€“ A great slow burn.  Itâ€™s weird and creepy and I really enjoy the setting of this big old house somewhere in northern UK I thinkâ€¦?</li><li><strong>Roma</strong> â€“ Again, I was underwhelmed at first, mainly due to the hype it had.  I always read â€œRoma should have won best pictures, this is an outrage, rabble rabble rabbleâ€, so I expected to be amazed.  In the end, it made a good impression on me, but it took some time to get used to its pace and â€œuneventfulâ€ storytelling</li><li><strong>Wendigo</strong> â€“ Iâ€™ve said before that, maybe if I watch it again in a different time and setting, I would be less impressed.  But still.. the memory I do have of watching this is good</li><li><strong>Kotoko</strong> â€“ If there was such a category as â€œdramatic horrorâ€ or something like that, this is it.  Itâ€™s a little psychological, mental and emotional horror more than anything outright, but I â€œgotâ€ it, even if the main character is in a much different life situation than me, itâ€™s still relatable</li><li><strong>Habit</strong> â€“ Another one thatâ€™s more dramatic and more of a personal story than some obvious horror.  Great setting with 90s NYC, and not the â€œtouristyâ€ parts of NYC</li><li><strong>Serial Mom</strong> â€“ Iâ€™m going to go ahead and toss this one in.  When thinking back on all the movies I watched, in terms of just how fun the experience was, this is up there.  Itâ€™s campy and I had to get used to that, but once I embraced the campyness, it all came together</li><li><strong>Cruising</strong> â€“ This is a tough one only because I feel like there were some pieces missing that could have really tied the room together and made this even better.  Still, as is, itâ€™s go Al Pacino and a very interesting look at a real sub-culture in that distinct early 80s NYC atmosphere.  And itâ€™s very slasher-like, which is a plus for me</li><li><strong>Dirty Harry</strong> â€“ The standard for the â€œplays-by-his-own-rulesâ€ cop kind of movie.  Maybe itâ€™s been overdone at this point, but this one was a fun watch for me</li>",
      "The first seven or so on that list were pretty easy to pick.  They had been on my mind as top movies for a while.  But the last three, I really had to look at the list and decide.. but I think I made the right choices..",
      "<strong>Honorable Mentions</strong>",
